<sn><md>### Why Mean Alone Can Be Misleading!

**“A group of friends earning 40k per year — and one friend is Bill Gates”**

**The Data (Annual Income of 6 Friends)**

Five normal friends earn:

```
40,000  
40,000  
40,000  
40,000  
40,000
```

One friend is Bill Gates:

```
100,000,000,000   (100 billion)
```

### Full dataset

```
40,000  
40,000  
40,000  
40,000  
40,000  
100,000,000,000
```

---

#### Calculate the Mean (Average)

$$
\text{Mean} = \frac{\text{sum of values}}{n}
$$

$$
= \frac{40k \times 5 + 100B}{6}
$$

Converting to numbers:

* Five friends: $5 \times 40,000 = 200,000$
* Bill Gates: $100,000,000,000$

$$
\text{Mean} = \frac{100,000,200,000}{6}
\approx 16,666,700,000
$$

**Mean ≈ 16.67 billion per person**

---

#### Why this mean is **misleading**

Does **anyone** except Bill Gates make anywhere near 16 billion per year?

No.

Do the five normal friends earn above 40k?<br>
No.

Do they remotely approach the group’s mean?<br>
No.

#### What Dispersion Shows (Why It Saves the Day)

##### Median

Sort the data:

```
40k, 40k, 40k, 40k, 40k, 100B
```

Median = average of 3rd and 4th values → both are 40k

$$
\text{Median} = 40,000
$$

The median correctly reflects what *typical* friends earn.

---

#### Standard Deviation (σ)

Standard deviation measures **how spread** the data are from the mean.

With a huge outlier, σ becomes enormous.

These “distances from mean” are massive → squaring makes them astronomically large →
**standard deviation becomes extremely huge**.

This tells us:

&gt; **The group’s incomes are extremely unequal.**

---

#### MAD (Mean Absolute Deviation)

MAD will also explode because of the outlier, but **not as badly** as standard deviation.

Still:<br>
MAD → huge<br>
Meaning → incomes are very unequally distributed.

### Final Interpretation (Easy Explanation)

**Mean alone says:**

&gt; “Everyone in this group earns ~16.7 billion per year.”

→ Completely false.

#### **Median says:**

&gt; “Typical income is 40k.”

→ Correct.

##### Standard deviation says:

&gt; “The spread is HUGE; incomes are extremely unequal.”

→ Shows existence of a massive outlier.

#### Why Dispersion Helps Here

Because dispersion measures (std dev, variance, MAD) **quantify the inequality**.
They tell you:

* Mean is being distorted
* Data contains extreme outliers
* Income distribution is not normal
* Typical value is far lower than mean
* You should use median, not mean
</md></sn><sn><md>### Simple Example

For data:
5, 7, 9

### Mean

$$
\bar{x} = \frac{5+7+9}{3} = 7
$$

#### Deviations

$$
5 - 7 = -2,\quad 7 - 7 = 0,\quad 9 - 7 = 2
$$

#### Dispersion Example

Range = 9 − 5 = 4
(Standard deviation, variance, etc., can also be calculated.)
